  <!-- HLR: HL-EXPL-1.1 (Example) -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>System Initialization Sequence</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall execute an initialization sequence at power-up that includes: hardware self-check, sensor availability check, actuator availability check, memory check for the mapping and planning data structures, and loading of configuration parameters required for exploration, mapping, planning, and run control.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Operating Modes</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide at least the following operating modes as internal states: IDLE, EXPLORATION, MAPPING, PATH_PLANNING, RETURN_TO_START, SECOND_RUN, and ERROR_HANDLING, and shall support transitioning between these modes according to the high-level task progression.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>State Persistence</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall persist the current internal map, robot pose estimate, and current mode into non-volatile memory at least once every 5 seconds during operation to allow recovery from power loss without full re-exploration.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-EXPL-1.2 Explore Maze -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Autonomous Exploration Control Loop</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a closed-loop exploration controller that, at a fixed control frequency of at least 20 Hz, reads processed sensor data, updates the robot pose estimate, updates the internal maze representation, selects the next motion command to explore yet-unvisited cells, and issues motion commands to the actuators without external operator intervention.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Frontier-Based Exploration Strategy</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.4</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a frontier-based exploration strategy where cells located at the boundary between known free space and unknown space (frontier cells) are identified, prioritized, and used as sub-goals for navigation until no reachable frontier cells remain.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Completion Criterion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.4</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall declare exploration complete and transition from EXPLORATION to RETURN_TO_START mode when either (a) no unknown cell is reachable from the current pose without passing through a blocked cell according to the internal map, or (b) the elapsed exploration time reaches 4 minutes and 30 seconds since start of EXPLORATION mode.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Start and Stop Conditions</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enter EXPLORATION mode automatically after successful initialization and shall stop exploration only when one of the following events occurs: exploration completion criterion is satisfied, a critical fault is detected, or an explicit stop command is received through a debug or service interface.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-EXPL-1.3 Wall Detection -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Obstacle Proximity Detection</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall calculate obstacle proximity distances in front, left, and right of the robot at least at 50 Hz using the available range or distance sensors and shall flag any direction as blocked when the measured distance is less than or equal to a configurable wall threshold distance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Motion Command Adjustment Near Walls</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall modify or override planned linear and angular velocity commands whenever obstacle proximity detection indicates a blocked direction, such that the resulting command does not move the robot towards the blocked direction and instead either stops or steers the robot away from the detected wall.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Wall Alignment Behavior</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a wall alignment behavior that, upon detecting walls on both left and right sides within a specified corridor threshold, adjusts the robot's orientation to minimize the difference between left and right wall distances, thereby keeping the robot centered in the corridor.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-MAP-2.1 Create Map -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Grid Map Representation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall maintain an internal 2D grid-based map of the maze, where each grid cell represents a fixed physical area of the maze, and shall store for each cell its occupancy state, visitation flag, and any associated metadata required for planning.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Pose Estimation for Mapping</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall estimate the robot's pose (position and orientation) within the map coordinate frame using at least wheel encoder data and optionally inertial measurements, updating the pose at a rate of at least 50 Hz to support accurate registration of sensor measurements into the grid map.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Map Update from Sensor Data</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall update the occupancy state and visitation flag of grid cells based on incoming sensor measurements and current pose, marking cells intersected by the sensor's line of sight without an obstacle as free and cells corresponding to detected obstacles as blocked.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Map Reset and Reinitialization</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide a mechanism to reset and reinitialize the internal map to all-unknown state, with the starting cell marked as free, when a new maze run is initiated.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-MAP-2.2 Cell Classification -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Occupancy States Definition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall classify each grid cell into exactly one of the following occupancy states: UNKNOWN (no reliable information), FREE (traversable space), or BLOCKED (occupied by a wall or obstacle), and shall store this state explicitly in the map data structure.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Reachability Computation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall determine whether a target cell is reachable from the current pose by searching over adjacent FREE cells in the grid map while treating BLOCKED and UNKNOWN cells as non-traversable, and shall expose this result to exploration and planning functions.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Visited Cell Tracking</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall maintain for each grid cell a visited flag that is set when the robot’s footprint enters the cell and shall use this visited information to distinguish between explored free areas and unexplored free areas.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-MAP-2.3 Time Constraint -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.1">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Global Mapping Time Limit</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enforce that the total time spent in EXPLORATION and MAPPING related modes from start of exploration until exploration completion shall not exceed 5 minutes.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Mapping Update Latency</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall ensure that the latency between receiving new sensor data and incorporating its effect into the internal map shall not exceed 100 milliseconds under nominal operating conditions.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-PLAN-3.1 Path Planning -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Grid-Based Path Planner</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a grid-based path planning algorithm that computes a collision-free path as an ordered sequence of adjacent FREE grid cells from a specified start cell to a specified goal cell using the current internal map.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Path Optimality Criterion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall minimize the total path cost defined as the sum of traversal costs of all cells along the path, where each FREE cell has a non-negative traversal cost and BLOCKED cells are assigned infinite cost so they are excluded from feasible paths.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Planning Time Constraint</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall compute a path for any planning request within 200 milliseconds for maps up to the maximum supported grid size, or indicate failure if no feasible path exists.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Replanning with Updated Map</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall trigger replanning when the internal map changes such that any cell on the currently executed path becomes BLOCKED, and shall compute an alternative path from the robot's current cell to the original goal if one exists.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Goal Selection for Target Cell</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall support selecting the maze's designated target cell as the goal for path planning either by predefined coordinates or by a specific cell classification, and shall pass this goal to the path planner for path computation.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RUN-4.1 Return to Start -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Start Cell Identification</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall mark the robot's initial cell at the beginning of exploration as the start cell in the internal map and shall retain this marking for use in later planning and execution phases.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Plan Path Back to Start</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Upon completion of exploration, the system shall compute a collision-free path from the robot's current cell to the start cell using the internal map and the path planning algorithm.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Execute Return-to-Start Path</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.1.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall convert the planned path to the start cell into a sequence of motion commands and execute them by controlling the actuators while continuing to apply wall avoidance to ensure that the robot physically returns to the start cell within a tolerance of one grid cell.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RUN-4.2 Second Run -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Initialization</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      After the robot has returned to the start cell, the system shall transition from RETURN_TO_START mode to SECOND_RUN mode without resetting or modifying the existing internal map or stored optimal path information.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Reuse of First-Run Map in Second Run</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall reuse the internal map created during the first exploration run as the basis for planning and executing the second run, without performing additional exploratory behavior or modifying cell occupancy except in response to newly detected obstacles that contradict the existing map.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RUN-4.3 Efficient Path Execution -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Compute Most Efficient Path for Second Run</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.2.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Before starting the second run, the system shall compute a path from the start cell to the target cell that minimizes the defined path cost and shall store this path as the reference second-run path.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Path Execution</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.3.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      During SECOND_RUN mode, the system shall follow the stored most efficient path by converting each path segment into motion commands and executing them sequentially while continuously enforcing wall detection and avoidance behaviors.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Time Optimization</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.3.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall configure traversal costs and motion command parameters for the second run such that, under nominal conditions without new obstacles, the second run arrival time at the target cell is less than or equal to the first run arrival time minus 10 percent.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RELIAB-5.1 Collision Avoidance -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Collision Avoidance Safety Layer</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a safety layer that monitors predicted robot trajectory for the next 0.5 seconds and shall override any motion command that would result in an estimated distance to any detected wall of less than a configurable safety distance, by issuing a stop or evasive maneuver command.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.1.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Maximum Allowed Contact Probability</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Under nominal operating conditions, the collision avoidance mechanisms shall be designed such that the probability of physical contact with walls during a complete exploration and second run does not exceed 1 percent over a statistically significant number of runs.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RELIAB-5.2 Fault Tolerance -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Plausibility Checking</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall perform plausibility checks on incoming sensor data by comparing each new measurement against recent measurements, expected ranges, and the current map, and shall flag measurements as faulty when they are inconsistent beyond configurable thresholds.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Redundant Sensor Fusion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      When multiple sensors provide information about the same physical quantity, the system shall fuse their data using a weighted or voting scheme and shall reduce the influence or discard readings flagged as faulty by the plausibility checks.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Degradation to Safe Behavior on Sensor Fault</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      If all sensors required for collision avoidance in a specific direction are flagged as faulty, the system shall reduce the robot speed to zero in that direction and either stop or retreat to a previously safe cell until valid sensor data is available or the run is aborted.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-INTERF-6.1 Sensor Processing -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Acquisition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall read raw data from all configured sensors according to the formats and update rates specified in the sensor data interface description and shall make this data available to the processing pipeline with accurate timestamps.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Filtering and Calibration</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall apply calibration parameters and filtering algorithms, such as bias correction and low-pass filtering, to the raw sensor data to produce processed measurements suitable for mapping, localization, and collision avoidance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Unified Sensor Data Interface</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide a unified internal interface for accessing processed sensor data, allowing mapping, planning, and control components to query the latest measurements using a common data structure and coordinate frame.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-INTERF-6.2 Actuator Control -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Motor Command Generation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall generate actuator commands according to the motor interface description, specifying desired wheel velocities or motor control signals, and shall transmit these commands at a rate of at least 20 Hz during motion.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Velocity and Acceleration Limits</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enforce configurable maximum linear and angular velocities and accelerations when generating actuator commands to ensure stable motion and to support effective collision avoidance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Emergency Stop Command</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall support an emergency stop function that, when triggered by the collision avoidance or fault tolerance components, immediately sends zero-velocity commands to all drive actuators and maintains this state until explicitly cleared.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>
</Requirements>
[2026-05-13--21:17:59]User: Your previous requirements were corrected

<Findings version="1" source="LLR" source_version="1">
  <Finding ID="LLR--1--1">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.1.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement references "configuration parameters required for exploration, mapping, planning, and run control" without defining or constraining these parameters. This introduces ambiguity for implementation and architecture (e.g., which parameters, where stored, how validated), making the requirement not fully implementable or testable.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Specify the minimal set of configuration parameter categories (e.g., motion limits, wall thresholds, map resolution, sensor calibration IDs, mode timeouts) and where they shall be stored (e.g., a configuration file or NVM block). For example: "The system shall load configuration parameters including at least motion limits, wall distance thresholds, map resolution, exploration timeout, and sensor calibration constants from non-volatile memory at initialization."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--2">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.1.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement defines operating modes including EXPLORATION, MAPPING, PATH_PLANNING, RETURN_TO_START, SECOND_RUN, and ERROR_HANDLING but leaves transitions "according to the high-level task progression" unspecified. This is ambiguous and insufficient to derive a consistent mode management architecture.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add explicit transition rules or reference additional LLRs that define them. For example: "The system shall define mode transition rules such that (a) after initialization the mode shall transition to EXPLORATION, (b) PATH_PLANNING and MAPPING shall be treated as substates or concurrent activities within EXPLORATION, RETURN_TO_START, and SECOND_RUN, and (c) ERROR_HANDLING shall be entered from any mode upon detection of a critical fault as defined in LL-RELIAB-5.2.x."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--3">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.1.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      State persistence is defined but recovery behavior after power loss is not. Without specifying how and when persisted data is restored, the architecture for startup and mode resumption cannot be clearly derived.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add a requirement describing recovery behavior, e.g.: "At startup, if a valid persisted state is available, the system shall restore the internal map, robot pose estimate, and current mode from non-volatile memory and resume operation in that mode, otherwise it shall perform a fresh initialization and start a new exploration."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--4">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.2.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement states a control frequency of "at least 20 Hz" and multiple operations within the loop but does not clarify what happens if the loop iteration exceeds this deadline. This can cause ambiguity in scheduling and real-time architecture decisions.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Specify timing semantics for overload, e.g.: "If a control loop iteration exceeds 50 ms, the system shall skip non-critical steps (such as frontier prioritization) in subsequent cycles until the average loop duration over the last N cycles is below 50 ms."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--5">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.2.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement uses "frontier cells are identified, prioritized" without defining the prioritization criterion (distance, information gain, cost, etc.). This leaves too much design freedom and can lead to inconsistent interpretations.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add at least a primary optimization criterion, e.g.: "Frontier cells shall be prioritized primarily by minimum estimated travel cost from the current pose, with a secondary criterion of expected information gain (number of adjacent UNKNOWN cells)."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--6">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.2.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement defines a 4 minutes 30 seconds limit for exploration completion while HLR HL-MAP-2.3 defines a 5 minutes mapping limit and LL-MAP-2.3.1 reiterates 5 minutes. The 4:30 value is not clearly justified and may be seen as contradicting or arbitrarily tightening the HLR constraint.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Clarify the relationship: either (a) explicitly state that 4:30 is a design margin to ensure compliance with the 5-minute HLR, or (b) align the value with exactly 5 minutes. For example: "…or (b) the elapsed exploration time reaches a configurable exploration timeout that shall be less than or equal to 5 minutes; default value shall be 4 minutes and 30 seconds."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--7">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.2.4</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The term "critical fault" is used without a definition or reference to a requirement that defines fault classes or criteria. This affects the clarity of when exploration shall stop.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Introduce or reference fault classification LLRs under HL-RELIAB-5.2. For example: "critical fault as defined by LL-RELIAB-5.2.x (e.g., loss of all collision-avoidance sensors, N consecutive pose estimation failures, or motor interface failure)."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--8">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.3.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The "configurable wall threshold distance" is not constrained (e.g., units, allowed range), which may impede testability and calibration architecture decisions.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Define units and bounds, e.g.: "…a configurable wall threshold distance specified in centimeters within the range [X, Y] as defined in the configuration parameters."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--9">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.3.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The "specified corridor threshold" is not linked to any configuration or defined range. Additionally, the algorithm for "minimize the difference between left and right wall distances" is unspecified, which may hinder consistent implementation across variants.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Reference a configuration parameter and give a basic algorithm indication, e.g.: "…within a specified corridor threshold (configurable parameter in centimeters). The system shall adjust angular velocity using a proportional controller on the difference between left and right wall distances."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--10">
    <ItemID>LL-MAP-2.1.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The grid map representation is specified but the map resolution and maximum supported grid size are not. This is problematic because other LLRs (e.g., LL-PLAN-3.1.3) reference "maximum supported grid size" and architectural memory/performance sizing requires explicit constraints.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add a resolution and maximum size constraint, either here or in an additional NFR, e.g.: "The map shall support a configurable cell size between A and B cm and shall support at least N x M cells, with the maximum grid size defined in a configuration parameter."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--11">
    <ItemID>LL-MAP-2.1.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The term "at least wheel encoder data and optionally inertial measurements" gives implementation freedom but lacks a fallback behavior when inertial measurements are absent or faulty, which is relevant for architecture (sensor fusion chain).
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Clarify required vs optional sensors and behavior on absence, e.g.: "Wheel encoder data shall be mandatory; inertial measurements, if available, shall be fused to improve pose estimation; if inertial sensors are not available, the system shall still meet pose accuracy requirements defined in [new NFR]."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--12">
    <ItemID>LL-MAP-2.1.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement describes updating occupancy and visitation but does not specify how conflicting measurements over time are handled (e.g., probabilistic vs. deterministic updates). This leaves ambiguity in the map update architecture.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add at least a high-level update policy, e.g.: "The system shall update occupancy using a probabilistic model (e.g., log-odds) or shall maintain a configurable confidence counter per cell, such that repeated contradictory measurements are resolved according to defined rules."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--13">
    <ItemID>LL-MAP-2.1.4</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      "When a new maze run is initiated" is not defined in terms of system events or modes, leading to ambiguity on who triggers map reset and when relative to other modes.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Define a trigger event or interface, for example: "A new maze run shall be initiated either at system startup after initialization or upon receiving a 'start new run' command from the debug/service interface, at which point the system shall reset and reinitialize the internal map…"
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--14">
    <ItemID>LL-MAP-2.2.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement says UNKNOWN cells are treated as non-traversable, but several exploration LLRs aim to navigate toward unknown regions. Without explicitly describing that reachability is used for exploration versus normal path planning, this can be confusing.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Clarify usage contexts: "For standard path planning the system shall treat UNKNOWN cells as non-traversable; exploration-specific logic may request reachability to a FREE neighbor of UNKNOWN regions rather than to UNKNOWN cells themselves."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--15">
    <ItemID>LL-MAP-2.2.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      "Robot’s footprint enters the cell" is not defined (shape, margin). This affects how visited flags are set and may impact architecture for collision checking and map indexing.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Define footprint model (e.g., circular with given radius) or reference a configuration parameter: "…when the center of the robot or any point within a circular footprint of radius R (configurable) lies inside the cell."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--16">
    <ItemID>LL-MAP-2.3.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement depends on LL-EXPL-1.2.1 and defines a global time limit, but it does not specify system behavior when 5 minutes is exceeded (e.g., abort, forced return to start, emergency stop), which is necessary for architecture and behavior design.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add behavior on time limit reach, e.g.: "If the time limit is exceeded before exploration completion, the system shall declare exploration complete, stop exploration behavior, and initiate RETURN_TO_START mode."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--17">
    <ItemID>LL-PLAN-3.1.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement describes a grid-based path planner but does not specify whether diagonal moves are allowed between cells. This leaves ambiguity in kinematic and planning architecture.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add adjacency definition, e.g.: "…as an ordered sequence of adjacent FREE grid cells, where adjacency is defined as four-connected (up, down, left, right) [or eight-connected, as specified]."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--18">
    <ItemID>LL-PLAN-3.1.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      While the requirement defines path cost and infinite cost for BLOCKED cells, it does not constrain traversal costs for FREE cells (e.g., allowed range or units). This can hinder testability of "optimality."
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Constrain cost values or define normalization: "Each FREE cell traversal cost shall be a non-negative real number within [0, C_max], where C_max is a configurable constant; the planner shall select the path with minimum total cost among all feasible paths."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--19">
    <ItemID>LL-PLAN-3.1.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The term "maximum supported grid size" is referenced but not defined anywhere in the LLR set, making the timing requirement loosely bound and difficult to verify.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Introduce an explicit requirement (likely NFR under mapping/architecture) defining the maximum grid dimensions or number of cells. Then reference that identifier here, e.g., "…for maps up to the maximum supported grid size as defined in LL-MAP-2.1.x."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--20">
    <ItemID>LL-PLAN-3.1.5</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The "specific cell classification" that denotes the target cell is not specified or linked to any classification requirement. Without this, the architecture for target identification is under-specified.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Either define a target-cell classification in a new mapping LLR (e.g., a TARGET state or tag) or constrain this requirement to explicit coordinates; e.g.: "…by predefined coordinates provided via configuration or by a dedicated TARGET flag stored in the map data structure."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--21">
    <ItemID>LL-RUN-4.1.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement specifies "within a tolerance of one grid cell" but does not specify how this is checked (position source, coordinate frame, or timing). This may affect design of localization and acceptance criteria.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Clarify the reference and method, e.g.: "…as determined by the current pose estimate within the map coordinate frame; the run shall be considered successful if the estimated robot cell index equals the start cell index or any of its four-connected neighbors."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--22">
    <ItemID>LL-RUN-4.2.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement allows modifying occupancy "in response to newly detected obstacles that contradict the existing map" but does not define how contradictions are detected or what happens to previously planned paths that use those cells.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Reference map update logic and replanning, e.g.: "Contradictions shall be detected based on LL-MAP-2.1.3 map update rules; if a cell on the second-run path becomes BLOCKED due to such an update, the system shall trigger replanning as described in LL-PLAN-3.1.4."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--23">
    <ItemID>LL-RUN-4.3.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement sets a probabilistic/relative performance constraint ("second run arrival time &lt;= first run arrival time minus 10 percent") but does not define how timing is measured, what constitutes "nominal conditions," or how to handle variance. This is weakly testable in a single-run context and difficult to turn into a concrete architectural performance requirement.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Reformulate into a more deterministic requirement, e.g.: "Under nominal conditions (defined as [...]), the system shall select speed and path parameters such that the expected second run time on a given maze is at least 10% shorter than the first run time, as measured from start cell departure to target cell arrival using the internal clock. Verification shall be performed statistically over N runs." Alternatively, convert this to a design goal documented outside strict requirements.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--24">
    <ItemID>LL-RELIAB-5.1.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement sets a probabilistic limit "does not exceed 1 percent over a statistically significant number of runs" without defining what "statistically significant" means, the operating conditions, or environment assumptions. This makes the requirement weakly testable and ambiguous.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Specify conditions and sample size, e.g.: "…shall not exceed 1 percent over at least 1000 complete runs in a representative set of mazes under nominal operating conditions (battery level range, surface friction, sensor noise level as specified in ...)."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--25">
    <ItemID>LL-RELIAB-5.2.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement describes plausibility checks but does not constrain update rates, fault flag propagation, or how flagged measurements impact downstream consumers (beyond later fusion). This may be insufficient to design a robust fault-handling architecture.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Extend the requirement set with additional LLRs specifying: (a) maximum delay between detecting implausibility and flagging a sensor as faulty, (b) how fault flags are exposed via the unified sensor interface, and (c) default behavior if plausibility checks fail intermittently.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--26">
    <ItemID>LL-RELIAB-5.2.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      "All sensors required for collision avoidance in a specific direction" is not defined. Without a mapping between directions and required sensors, it is hard to design a clear architecture for degradation logic.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Define or reference a mapping in an additional requirement, e.g.: "The system shall define, in configuration, which sensors are required for forward, left, and right collision avoidance. If all sensors in the configured set for a given direction are faulty, the behavior described shall be executed."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--27">
    <ItemID>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement references an external "sensor data interface description" without capturing key constraints (e.g., minimum supported update rate, maximum number of sensors, data size limits) in the LLR set. This dependency on an external document, if not controlled as part of the requirements, weakens the ability to derive a complete architecture from the LLRs alone.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add complementary LLRs that summarize essential constraints from the interface description (e.g., "The system shall support up to N range sensors and M encoders with update rates up to X Hz and message sizes up to Y bytes"). Alternatively, formally include the interface description as a referenced specification under configuration control.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--28">
    <ItemID>LL-INTERF-6.1.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The "unified internal interface for accessing processed sensor data" is only described at a high level. There is no specification of required query types (e.g., latest value, time-window queries), latency constraints, or data consistency guarantees, which are needed to design the interface and its implementation.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add one or more LLRs specifying: (a) that consumers shall be able to query the latest measurement per sensor and time-stamped histories for at least T seconds, (b) maximum allowed latency between acquisition and availability through the unified interface, and (c) thread-safety or concurrency expectations.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--29">
    <ItemID>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      The requirement defines command rate but not command latency or maximum tolerated jitter, which are important for architecture and control-loop stability.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add timing constraints, e.g.: "The system shall ensure that the latency between generating and transmitting a motor command does not exceed L milliseconds and that command rate jitter remains within ±J% of the nominal 20 Hz rate under nominal load."
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--30">
    <ItemID>LL-INTERF-6.2.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The emergency stop function is specified but there is no requirement defining the maximum reaction time from trigger detection to actuators receiving zero-velocity commands. This is critical for safety and architecture (e.g., prioritization and preemption).
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add a timing requirement, e.g.: "From the moment an emergency stop is triggered, the system shall send zero-velocity commands to all drive actuators within T milliseconds." Also, clarify whether emergency stop can be triggered from external interfaces in addition to collision avoidance and fault tolerance.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--31">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.2.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      There is no explicit LLR describing the architecture-level separation between modules/components (e.g., exploration controller, mapping module, planner, motion controller, safety layer) even though the behavior implies such decomposition. This makes it harder to derive a clear architecture design purely from the LLR set.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Introduce a small set of structural LLRs (still functional in nature) that explicitly state that exploration, mapping, planning, motion control, and safety are separate logical components with defined interfaces (e.g., "The system shall implement a Mapping component that provides map update services to the Exploration and Planning components via ..."). These do not impose implementation detail but are sufficient to guide architecture.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>
</Findings> 

Incorporate them into your previous requirements.

This is the previous version of your requirements:
<Requirements version="1" hierarchy="LLR">
  <!-- HLR: HL-EXPL-1.1 (Example) -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>System Initialization Sequence</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall execute an initialization sequence at power-up that includes: hardware self-check, sensor availability check, actuator availability check, memory check for the mapping and planning data structures, and loading of configuration parameters required for exploration, mapping, planning, and run control.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Operating Modes</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide at least the following operating modes as internal states: IDLE, EXPLORATION, MAPPING, PATH_PLANNING, RETURN_TO_START, SECOND_RUN, and ERROR_HANDLING, and shall support transitioning between these modes according to the high-level task progression.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>State Persistence</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall persist the current internal map, robot pose estimate, and current mode into non-volatile memory at least once every 5 seconds during operation to allow recovery from power loss without full re-exploration.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-EXPL-1.2 Explore Maze -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Autonomous Exploration Control Loop</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a closed-loop exploration controller that, at a fixed control frequency of at least 20 Hz, reads processed sensor data, updates the robot pose estimate, updates the internal maze representation, selects the next motion command to explore yet-unvisited cells, and issues motion commands to the actuators without external operator intervention.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Frontier-Based Exploration Strategy</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.4</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a frontier-based exploration strategy where cells located at the boundary between known free space and unknown space (frontier cells) are identified, prioritized, and used as sub-goals for navigation until no reachable frontier cells remain.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Completion Criterion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.4</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall declare exploration complete and transition from EXPLORATION to RETURN_TO_START mode when either (a) no unknown cell is reachable from the current pose without passing through a blocked cell according to the internal map, or (b) the elapsed exploration time reaches 4 minutes and 30 seconds since start of EXPLORATION mode.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Start and Stop Conditions</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enter EXPLORATION mode automatically after successful initialization and shall stop exploration only when one of the following events occurs: exploration completion criterion is satisfied, a critical fault is detected, or an explicit stop command is received through a debug or service interface.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-EXPL-1.3 Wall Detection -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Obstacle Proximity Detection</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall calculate obstacle proximity distances in front, left, and right of the robot at least at 50 Hz using the available range or distance sensors and shall flag any direction as blocked when the measured distance is less than or equal to a configurable wall threshold distance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Motion Command Adjustment Near Walls</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall modify or override planned linear and angular velocity commands whenever obstacle proximity detection indicates a blocked direction, such that the resulting command does not move the robot towards the blocked direction and instead either stops or steers the robot away from the detected wall.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Wall Alignment Behavior</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a wall alignment behavior that, upon detecting walls on both left and right sides within a specified corridor threshold, adjusts the robot's orientation to minimize the difference between left and right wall distances, thereby keeping the robot centered in the corridor.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-MAP-2.1 Create Map -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Grid Map Representation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall maintain an internal 2D grid-based map of the maze, where each grid cell represents a fixed physical area of the maze, and shall store for each cell its occupancy state, visitation flag, and any associated metadata required for planning.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Pose Estimation for Mapping</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall estimate the robot's pose (position and orientation) within the map coordinate frame using at least wheel encoder data and optionally inertial measurements, updating the pose at a rate of at least 50 Hz to support accurate registration of sensor measurements into the grid map.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Map Update from Sensor Data</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall update the occupancy state and visitation flag of grid cells based on incoming sensor measurements and current pose, marking cells intersected by the sensor's line of sight without an obstacle as free and cells corresponding to detected obstacles as blocked.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Map Reset and Reinitialization</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide a mechanism to reset and reinitialize the internal map to all-unknown state, with the starting cell marked as free, when a new maze run is initiated.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-MAP-2.2 Cell Classification -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Occupancy States Definition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall classify each grid cell into exactly one of the following occupancy states: UNKNOWN (no reliable information), FREE (traversable space), or BLOCKED (occupied by a wall or obstacle), and shall store this state explicitly in the map data structure.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Reachability Computation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall determine whether a target cell is reachable from the current pose by searching over adjacent FREE cells in the grid map while treating BLOCKED and UNKNOWN cells as non-traversable, and shall expose this result to exploration and planning functions.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Visited Cell Tracking</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall maintain for each grid cell a visited flag that is set when the robot’s footprint enters the cell and shall use this visited information to distinguish between explored free areas and unexplored free areas.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-MAP-2.3 Time Constraint -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.1">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Global Mapping Time Limit</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enforce that the total time spent in EXPLORATION and MAPPING related modes from start of exploration until exploration completion shall not exceed 5 minutes.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Mapping Update Latency</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall ensure that the latency between receiving new sensor data and incorporating its effect into the internal map shall not exceed 100 milliseconds under nominal operating conditions.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-PLAN-3.1 Path Planning -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Grid-Based Path Planner</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a grid-based path planning algorithm that computes a collision-free path as an ordered sequence of adjacent FREE grid cells from a specified start cell to a specified goal cell using the current internal map.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Path Optimality Criterion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall minimize the total path cost defined as the sum of traversal costs of all cells along the path, where each FREE cell has a non-negative traversal cost and BLOCKED cells are assigned infinite cost so they are excluded from feasible paths.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Planning Time Constraint</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall compute a path for any planning request within 200 milliseconds for maps up to the maximum supported grid size, or indicate failure if no feasible path exists.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Replanning with Updated Map</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall trigger replanning when the internal map changes such that any cell on the currently executed path becomes BLOCKED, and shall compute an alternative path from the robot's current cell to the original goal if one exists.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Goal Selection for Target Cell</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall support selecting the maze's designated target cell as the goal for path planning either by predefined coordinates or by a specific cell classification, and shall pass this goal to the path planner for path computation.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RUN-4.1 Return to Start -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Start Cell Identification</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall mark the robot's initial cell at the beginning of exploration as the start cell in the internal map and shall retain this marking for use in later planning and execution phases.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Plan Path Back to Start</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Upon completion of exploration, the system shall compute a collision-free path from the robot's current cell to the start cell using the internal map and the path planning algorithm.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Execute Return-to-Start Path</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.1.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall convert the planned path to the start cell into a sequence of motion commands and execute them by controlling the actuators while continuing to apply wall avoidance to ensure that the robot physically returns to the start cell within a tolerance of one grid cell.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RUN-4.2 Second Run -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Initialization</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      After the robot has returned to the start cell, the system shall transition from RETURN_TO_START mode to SECOND_RUN mode without resetting or modifying the existing internal map or stored optimal path information.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Reuse of First-Run Map in Second Run</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall reuse the internal map created during the first exploration run as the basis for planning and executing the second run, without performing additional exploratory behavior or modifying cell occupancy except in response to newly detected obstacles that contradict the existing map.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RUN-4.3 Efficient Path Execution -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Compute Most Efficient Path for Second Run</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.2.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Before starting the second run, the system shall compute a path from the start cell to the target cell that minimizes the defined path cost and shall store this path as the reference second-run path.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Path Execution</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.3.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      During SECOND_RUN mode, the system shall follow the stored most efficient path by converting each path segment into motion commands and executing them sequentially while continuously enforcing wall detection and avoidance behaviors.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Time Optimization</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.3.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall configure traversal costs and motion command parameters for the second run such that, under nominal conditions without new obstacles, the second run arrival time at the target cell is less than or equal to the first run arrival time minus 10 percent.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RELIAB-5.1 Collision Avoidance -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Collision Avoidance Safety Layer</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a safety layer that monitors predicted robot trajectory for the next 0.5 seconds and shall override any motion command that would result in an estimated distance to any detected wall of less than a configurable safety distance, by issuing a stop or evasive maneuver command.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.1.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Maximum Allowed Contact Probability</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Under nominal operating conditions, the collision avoidance mechanisms shall be designed such that the probability of physical contact with walls during a complete exploration and second run does not exceed 1 percent over a statistically significant number of runs.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RELIAB-5.2 Fault Tolerance -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Plausibility Checking</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall perform plausibility checks on incoming sensor data by comparing each new measurement against recent measurements, expected ranges, and the current map, and shall flag measurements as faulty when they are inconsistent beyond configurable thresholds.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Redundant Sensor Fusion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      When multiple sensors provide information about the same physical quantity, the system shall fuse their data using a weighted or voting scheme and shall reduce the influence or discard readings flagged as faulty by the plausibility checks.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Degradation to Safe Behavior on Sensor Fault</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      If all sensors required for collision avoidance in a specific direction are flagged as faulty, the system shall reduce the robot speed to zero in that direction and either stop or retreat to a previously safe cell until valid sensor data is available or the run is aborted.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-INTERF-6.1 Sensor Processing -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Acquisition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall read raw data from all configured sensors according to the formats and update rates specified in the sensor data interface description and shall make this data available to the processing pipeline with accurate timestamps.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Filtering and Calibration</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall apply calibration parameters and filtering algorithms, such as bias correction and low-pass filtering, to the raw sensor data to produce processed measurements suitable for mapping, localization, and collision avoidance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Unified Sensor Data Interface</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide a unified internal interface for accessing processed sensor data, allowing mapping, planning, and control components to query the latest measurements using a common data structure and coordinate frame.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-INTERF-6.2 Actuator Control -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Motor Command Generation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall generate actuator commands according to the motor interface description, specifying desired wheel velocities or motor control signals, and shall transmit these commands at a rate of at least 20 Hz during motion.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Velocity and Acceleration Limits</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enforce configurable maximum linear and angular velocities and accelerations when generating actuator commands to ensure stable motion and to support effective collision avoidance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Emergency Stop Command</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall support an emergency stop function that, when triggered by the collision avoidance or fault tolerance components, immediately sends zero-velocity commands to all drive actuators and maintains this state until explicitly cleared.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>
</Requirements>

