[2026-05-13--21:19:05]Agent: <Requirements version="2" hierarchy="LLR">
  <!-- HLR: HL-EXPL-1.1 (Example / System-Level) -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>System Initialization Sequence</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall execute an initialization sequence at power-up that includes: hardware self-check, sensor availability check, actuator availability check, memory check for the mapping and planning data structures, and loading of configuration parameters including at least motion limits, wall distance thresholds, map resolution and maximum grid size, exploration and mapping timeouts, corridor threshold, robot footprint radius, and sensor calibration constants from non-volatile memory.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Operating Modes and Transitions</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.4</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide at least the following operating modes as internal states: IDLE, EXPLORATION, RETURN_TO_START, SECOND_RUN, and ERROR_HANDLING, and shall define mode transition rules such that (a) after successful initialization in IDLE the mode shall transition to EXPLORATION when a new maze run is initiated, (b) mapping and path planning shall be executed as internal activities or substates within EXPLORATION, RETURN_TO_START, and SECOND_RUN and shall not appear as externally selectable modes, (c) upon exploration completion the mode shall transition from EXPLORATION to RETURN_TO_START, (d) upon successful arrival at the start cell the mode shall transition from RETURN_TO_START to SECOND_RUN, (e) upon completion of the second run the mode shall transition to IDLE, and (f) ERROR_HANDLING shall be entered from any mode upon detection of a critical fault as defined in LL-RELIAB-5.2.4.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>State Persistence</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall persist the current internal map, robot pose estimate, and current mode into non-volatile memory at least once every 5 seconds during operation to allow recovery from power loss without full re-exploration.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Recovery from Persisted State</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      At startup, if a valid persisted state is available, the system shall restore the internal map, robot pose estimate, and current mode from non-volatile memory and resume operation in that mode; otherwise, it shall perform a fresh initialization, reset the internal map, and start a new exploration.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Structural decomposition to support architecture (Finding 31) -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.1.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Logical Component Separation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.3</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement at least the following logical software components with well-defined interfaces: an Exploration Controller component responsible for exploration strategy and mode management, a Mapping component responsible for maintaining and updating the internal map, a Planning component responsible for path computation, a Motion Control component responsible for converting paths into actuator commands, and a Safety component responsible for collision avoidance and emergency stop handling; these components shall communicate only via defined data interfaces for pose, map, paths, motion commands, and sensor status.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-EXPL-1.2 Explore Maze -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Autonomous Exploration Control Loop</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.5</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a closed-loop exploration controller that, at a nominal control period of 50 milliseconds (20 Hz), reads processed sensor data, updates the robot pose estimate, updates the internal maze representation, selects the next motion command to explore yet-unvisited cells, and issues motion commands to the actuators without external operator intervention; if the average loop duration over the last 20 cycles exceeds 50 milliseconds, the controller shall temporarily skip non-critical steps (frontier prioritization and global replanning) and perform only pose update, safety checks, and local obstacle avoidance until the average loop duration over the last 20 cycles is below or equal to 50 milliseconds.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Frontier-Based Exploration Strategy</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.4</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a frontier-based exploration strategy where grid cells located at the boundary between known FREE space and UNKNOWN space (frontier cells) are identified and used as sub-goals for navigation until no reachable frontier cells remain, and shall prioritize frontier cells primarily by minimum estimated travel cost from the current pose as given by the path planner, with a secondary criterion of maximum expected information gain measured as the number of adjacent UNKNOWN cells.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Completion Criterion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.4</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.3.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall declare exploration complete and request a transition from EXPLORATION mode to RETURN_TO_START mode when either (a) no UNKNOWN cell is reachable from the current pose without passing through a BLOCKED cell according to the internal map, or (b) the elapsed exploration time since start of EXPLORATION mode reaches a configurable exploration timeout parameter whose value shall be less than or equal to 5 minutes and whose default value shall be 4 minutes and 30 seconds.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Start and Stop Conditions</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.4</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enter EXPLORATION mode automatically after successful initialization when a new maze run is initiated and shall stop exploration only when one of the following events occurs: the exploration completion criterion defined in LL-EXPL-1.2.3 is satisfied, a critical fault as defined in LL-RELIAB-5.2.4 is detected, or an explicit stop command is received through a debug or service interface.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-EXPL-1.3 Wall Detection -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Obstacle Proximity Detection</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall calculate obstacle proximity distances in front, left, and right of the robot at least at 50 Hz using the available range or distance sensors and shall flag any direction as blocked when the measured distance in that direction is less than or equal to a configurable wall threshold distance specified in centimeters within a configurable range of at least 1 cm to 50 cm.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Motion Command Adjustment Near Walls</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall modify or override planned linear and angular velocity commands whenever obstacle proximity detection indicates a blocked direction, such that the resulting motion does not move the robot towards the blocked direction and instead either stops or steers the robot away from the detected wall while maintaining adherence to configured velocity and acceleration limits.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Wall Alignment Behavior</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a wall alignment behavior that, upon detecting walls on both left and right sides within a configurable corridor threshold distance specified in centimeters, adjusts the robot's orientation using a proportional controller on the difference between left and right wall distances in order to minimize that difference and thereby keep the robot centered in the corridor.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-MAP-2.1 Create Map -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Grid Map Representation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall maintain an internal 2D grid-based map of the maze, where each grid cell represents a fixed physical area of the maze, and shall store for each cell its occupancy state, visitation flag, and any associated metadata required for planning; the grid cell size shall be configurable within a range of at least 1 cm to 10 cm, and the map implementation shall support a maximum grid size defined as a configurable number of rows and columns with at least 64 by 64 cells.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Pose Estimation for Mapping</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall estimate the robot's pose (position and orientation) within the map coordinate frame at a rate of at least 50 Hz using wheel encoder data as a mandatory input and fusing inertial measurements when such sensors are available and not flagged as faulty; if inertial sensors are not available or are flagged as faulty, the system shall perform pose estimation based solely on wheel encoder data while maintaining compatibility with all mapping and planning functions.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Map Update from Sensor Data</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall update the occupancy state and visitation flag of grid cells based on incoming sensor measurements and current pose by applying a consistent update policy in which each cell maintains an occupancy confidence value that is increased when measurements indicate an obstacle and decreased when measurements indicate free space, and the occupancy state is set to BLOCKED or FREE when the confidence crosses configurable thresholds; repeated contradictory measurements shall be resolved according to these thresholds, and cells intersected by a sensor's line of sight without an obstacle shall have their occupancy confidence decreased toward FREE while cells corresponding to detected obstacles shall have their occupancy confidence increased toward BLOCKED.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Map Reset and Reinitialization</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide a mechanism to reset and reinitialize the internal map to an all-UNKNOWN state, with the starting cell marked as FREE, whenever a new maze run is initiated, where a new maze run is initiated either automatically at system startup after successful initialization or upon receiving a "start new run" command from the debug or service interface while in IDLE mode.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-MAP-2.2 Cell Classification -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Occupancy States Definition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall classify each grid cell into exactly one of the following occupancy states: UNKNOWN (no reliable information), FREE (traversable space), or BLOCKED (occupied by a wall or obstacle), and shall store this state explicitly in the map data structure.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Reachability Computation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall determine whether a target cell is reachable from the current pose by searching over adjacent FREE cells in the grid map while treating BLOCKED and UNKNOWN cells as non-traversable for standard path planning, and shall expose this result to exploration and planning functions; exploration-specific logic shall request reachability to FREE cells that are neighbors of UNKNOWN regions rather than to UNKNOWN cells themselves when navigating toward unexplored areas.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Visited Cell Tracking</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall maintain for each grid cell a visited flag that is set when the center of the robot or any point within a circular footprint of radius equal to a configurable footprint radius lies inside the cell in the map coordinate frame, and shall use this visited information to distinguish between explored FREE areas and unexplored FREE areas.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Target Cell Flagging</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall support marking exactly one grid cell in the internal map as the maze target cell by storing a dedicated TARGET flag in that cell, where this flag is either configured by predefined coordinates before a run or set via a dedicated configuration or debug interface.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-MAP-2.3 Time Constraint -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.1">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Global Mapping Time Limit</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.2.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enforce that the total time spent from the start of EXPLORATION mode until exploration is declared complete shall not exceed 5 minutes, and if this time limit is exceeded before the exploration completion condition based on reachability is satisfied, the system shall declare exploration complete, stop exploration behavior, and initiate the RETURN_TO_START mode.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Mapping Update Latency</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall ensure that the latency between receiving new sensor data and incorporating its effect into the internal map shall not exceed 100 milliseconds under nominal operating conditions.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-PLAN-3.1 Path Planning -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Grid-Based Path Planner</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a grid-based path planning algorithm that computes a collision-free path as an ordered sequence of adjacent FREE grid cells from a specified start cell to a specified goal cell using the current internal map, where adjacency is defined as four-connected (up, down, left, right) neighbors in the grid.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Path Optimality Criterion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall minimize the total path cost defined as the sum of traversal costs of all cells along the path, where each FREE cell has a traversal cost represented as a non-negative real number within a configurable range from 0 to a maximum cost constant, and BLOCKED cells are assigned infinite cost so they are excluded from feasible paths; the planner shall select the path with minimum total cost among all feasible paths between the given start and goal cells.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Planning Time Constraint</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall compute a path for any planning request within 200 milliseconds for maps whose number of rows and columns do not exceed the configured maximum grid size supported by the map representation, or shall indicate failure if no feasible path exists.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Replanning with Updated Map</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall trigger replanning when the internal map changes such that any cell on the currently executed path becomes BLOCKED or otherwise non-traversable, and shall compute an alternative path from the robot's current cell to the original goal if one exists; if no alternative path exists, the planner shall report failure to the Exploration Controller or Run Controller.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Goal Selection for Target Cell</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.3</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.2.4</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall support selecting the maze's designated target cell as the goal for path planning either by predefined coordinates configured before the run or by using the cell currently marked with the TARGET flag in the map data structure, and shall pass this goal to the path planner for path computation.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RUN-4.1 Return to Start -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Start Cell Identification</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall mark the robot's initial cell at the beginning of exploration as the start cell in the internal map by setting a dedicated START flag for that cell and shall retain this marking for use in later planning and execution phases.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Plan Path Back to Start</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Upon completion of exploration, the system shall compute a collision-free path from the robot's current cell to the start cell using the internal map and the path planning algorithm.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Execute Return-to-Start Path</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.1.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall convert the planned path to the start cell into a sequence of motion commands and execute them by controlling the actuators while continuing to apply wall avoidance, and shall consider the return-to-start run successful if, according to the current pose estimate in the map coordinate frame, the index of the cell containing the robot center is equal to the start cell index or to any of its four-connected neighbor cell indices.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RUN-4.2 Second Run -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Initialization</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.1.3</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.1.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      After the robot has successfully returned to the start cell, the system shall transition from RETURN_TO_START mode to SECOND_RUN mode without resetting or modifying the existing internal map or stored optimal path information.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Reuse of First-Run Map in Second Run</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.3</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.4</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall reuse the internal map created during the first exploration run as the basis for planning and executing the second run, without performing additional exploratory behavior, and shall modify cell occupancy only in response to newly detected obstacles that contradict the existing map according to the map update rules in LL-MAP-2.1.3; if such an update causes a cell on the second-run path to become BLOCKED, the system shall trigger replanning for the second run as described in LL-PLAN-3.1.4.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RUN-4.3 Efficient Path Execution -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Compute Most Efficient Path for Second Run</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.2.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-PLAN-3.1.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Before starting the second run, the system shall compute a path from the start cell to the target cell that minimizes the defined path cost over all feasible paths in the current internal map and shall store this path as the reference second-run path for execution.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Path Execution</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.3.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.2</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      During SECOND_RUN mode, the system shall follow the stored most efficient path by converting each path segment into motion commands and executing them sequentially while continuously enforcing wall detection and avoidance behaviors and respecting configured velocity and acceleration limits.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Performance Goal</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RUN-4.3.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Under nominal operating conditions defined as fully charged battery, level surface within specified friction range, and sensor noise within specified limits, the system shall select speed and path parameters for the second run such that the expected second-run travel time on a given maze, measured from start cell departure to target cell arrival using the internal system clock, is at least 10 percent shorter than the first-run travel time as demonstrated statistically over a test campaign of at least 100 runs; this requirement shall be treated as a performance goal and used to guide parameter selection and tuning.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RELIAB-5.1 Collision Avoidance -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Collision Avoidance Safety Layer</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-EXPL-1.3.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a safety layer that monitors the predicted robot trajectory for the next 0.5 seconds based on current motion commands and obstacle proximity information, and shall override any motion command that would result in an estimated distance to any detected wall of less than a configurable safety distance by issuing a stop or evasive maneuver command through the actuator interface.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.1.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Maximum Allowed Contact Probability</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Under nominal operating conditions defined as battery level within the manufacturer-recommended range, operation on a flat surface with friction coefficient within the specified interval, and sensor noise within specified limits, the collision avoidance mechanisms shall be designed such that the proportion of complete runs (including exploration, return to start, and second run) in which any physical contact with walls occurs does not exceed 1 percent over at least 1000 complete runs executed in a representative set of mazes.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-RELIAB-5.2 Fault Tolerance -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Plausibility Checking</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-MAP-2.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall perform plausibility checks on incoming sensor data at the same rate at which data is acquired by comparing each new measurement against recent measurements from the same sensor, expected numeric ranges, and the current map, and shall flag measurements as faulty when they are inconsistent beyond configurable thresholds; the system shall propagate a fault flag for the affected sensor to all consumers within 100 milliseconds of detecting implausibility.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Redundant Sensor Fusion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      When multiple sensors provide information about the same physical quantity, the system shall fuse their data using a weighted or voting scheme that reduces the influence of or discards readings flagged as faulty by the plausibility checks, such that fused outputs clearly indicate their validity status to downstream consumers.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Degradation to Safe Behavior on Sensor Fault</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.1.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.5</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      If all sensors configured for collision avoidance in a specific direction are flagged as faulty, the system shall reduce the robot speed command to zero in that direction and either stop the robot or command it to retreat along the previously executed path to a cell that was last confirmed as safe, and shall maintain this degraded behavior until at least one required sensor for that direction is again providing plausible data or the run is aborted.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Fault Classification and Critical Faults</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall classify detected faults into at least non-critical and critical categories and shall treat as critical faults any of the following conditions: loss of all sensors required for forward collision avoidance as defined in LL-RELIAB-5.2.5, detection of N consecutive pose estimation failures where N is a configurable parameter, or loss of communication with the motor control interface; upon detection of a critical fault, the system shall transition to ERROR_HANDLING mode and trigger an emergency stop.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Mapping of Sensors to Collision Avoidance Directions</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall define, via configuration parameters, which sensors or sensor groups are required for collision avoidance in at least the forward, left, and right directions, and shall use this mapping to determine when all sensors required for collision avoidance in a given direction are faulty for the purposes of degradation behavior in LL-RELIAB-5.2.3.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-INTERF-6.1 Sensor Processing -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Acquisition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall read raw data from all configured sensors according to their specified formats and shall support at least 8 range or distance sensors and 4 encoder channels with individual update rates up to 100 Hz and individual message sizes up to 64 bytes, and shall make all acquired data available to the processing pipeline with timestamps having a resolution of at least 1 millisecond.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Filtering and Calibration</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall apply calibration parameters and filtering algorithms, including at least offset and scale correction and low-pass filtering, to the raw sensor data to produce processed measurements suitable for mapping, localization, and collision avoidance, and shall apply the latest available calibration constants loaded during initialization.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Unified Sensor Data Interface</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.2</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide a unified internal interface for accessing processed sensor data that allows mapping, planning, motion control, and safety components to (a) query the latest processed measurement and validity status for each sensor, and (b) retrieve a time-stamped history of processed measurements for each sensor for at least the last 5 seconds, and shall ensure that processed data becomes available through this interface with a latency not exceeding 50 milliseconds from acquisition under nominal load and that concurrent access by multiple components does not lead to inconsistent views of individual measurements.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Propagation of Sensor Fault Status</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-RELIAB-5.2.1</DependsOn>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.1.3</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The unified sensor data interface shall expose, for each sensor, a fault status flag and last-fault timestamp generated by the plausibility checking logic, and shall update these fields within 100 milliseconds of a change in sensor fault status so that all consuming components can adapt their behavior accordingly.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- HLR: HL-INTERF-6.2 Actuator Control -->
  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Motor Command Generation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall generate actuator commands according to the motor interface description, specifying desired wheel velocities or motor control signals, and shall transmit these commands at a nominal rate of at least 20 Hz during motion, ensuring that the latency between generating a motor command and transmitting it on the actuator interface does not exceed 20 milliseconds and that the command transmission rate jitter remains within plus or minus 10 percent of the nominal rate under nominal computational load.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Velocity and Acceleration Limits</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enforce configurable maximum linear and angular velocities and accelerations when generating actuator commands, such that no command exceeds these limits, in order to ensure stable motion and to support effective collision avoidance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Emergency Stop Command</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <DependsOn>LL-INTERF-6.2.1</DependsOn>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall support an emergency stop function that can be triggered by the collision avoidance component, the fault tolerance component, or an external debug or safety interface, and that, from the moment of trigger detection, shall send zero-velocity commands to all drive actuators within 100 milliseconds and maintain this zero-velocity state until an explicit clear-emergency command is received and all critical fault conditions are resolved.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>
</Requirements>
